Barring some unforeseen twist of fate, Shari Redstone will
likely soon announce that Paramount Global has agreed to settle a lawsuit b=
rought by President Trump against CBS News=E2=80=99s 60 Minutes=E2=80=94the=
 latest in a string of settlements brokered by media organizations with the=
 ostensible hope of avoiding protracted public legal battles with the White=
 House or unwanted federal intervention in their business dealings. As has =
been the case with Disney and Meta, Paramount will likely pay tens of milli=
ons of dollars to the Trump Presidential
Library. And while initial reports suggest the settlement talks may not res=
ult in a deal, I am reliably told that Shari has already made up her mind.

=C2=A0

Of all his recent lawsuits, Trump=E2=80=99s case against 60 Minutes has the=
 least merit, according to legal experts. In brief, CBS=E2=80=99s Face the =
Nation edited a clip of a 60 Minutes interview with Kamala Harris to
include one part of her answer to a question about the Middle East=E2=80=94=
a widespread and longstanding practice in television news=E2=80=94while the=
 actual 60 Minutes broadcast included a different portion of her answer. Tr=
ump=E2=80=99s lawyers accused the network of =E2=80=9Cdeceptive doctoring,=
=E2=80=9D a claim the network flatly denied. Meanwhile, legal experts calle=
d his lawsuit against the company =E2=80=9Cfrivolous=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9C=
ridiculous,=E2=80=9D noting that CBS was well within its First Amendment pr=
otections.

From Shari=E2=80=99s vantage point, the practical concerns likely outweigh =
the ethical. She is on the cusp of closing a tortured $8 billion deal to se=
ll Paramount to Skydance=E2=80=94a deal that Trump=E2=80=99s Federal Commun=
ications Commission can block, or at least delay. Trump=E2=80=99s new F.C.C=
=2E chair, Brendan Carr, has said he in=
tends to investigate the 60 Minutes ma=
tter as part of his review of the merger, and has asked CBS News for unedit=
ed footage and a transcript of
the Harris interview=E2=80=94which the company agreed to hand over on Frida=
y afternoon.=C2=A0

After presiding over the decline of her father Sumner=E2=80=99s media empir=
e, holding on to it for far too long, and then finally arriving at acceptab=
le terms for a deal, Shari is understandably eager to dispense with any ele=
venth-hour roadblocks. Meanwhile, the Ellisons, Gerry Cardinale, and
Jeff Shell are surely happy to have Shari do the dirty work before handing =
off the asset. Larry Ellison, after all, is a card-carrying member of Trump=
=E2=80=99s broligarchy, and Oracle is a participant in Stargate and an appa=
rent contender for TikTok, if it plays out that way. Shari=E2=80=99s making=
 his life easier.

=C2=A0

Presumably, a similar realpolitik logic persuaded
Bob Iger to greenlight Disney=E2=80=99s $16 million payment to the presiden=
t-elect after he sued ABC News over George Stephanopoulos=E2=80=99s claim t=
hat Trump had been found civilly liable for =E2=80=9Craping=E2=80=9D E. Jea=
n Carroll when, in fact, he had been found liable for =E2=80=9Csexual abuse=
=2E=E2=80=9D Sure, George was also likely=20=
within his First Amendment rights;=20=
even the judge in the case acknowledged that =E2=80=9Crape=E2=80=9D was the=
 layman=E2=80=99s term, albeit not the legal one, for Trump=E2=80=99s actio=
ns.
But if you=E2=80=99re a $200 billion publicly traded company, and about to =
buy Fubo, why get involved in a costly and embarrassing legal battle=E2=80=
=94inevitably, George and Bob would have been forced to hand over their tex=
t messages and emails=E2=80=94when you can make the whole problem go away f=
or a relative pittance? Ditto Mark Zuckerberg, who was well within his righ=
ts to terminate Trump=E2=80=99s social media accounts for terms of service =
violation after January 6, but doesn=E2=80=99t want to lose his
seat at Trump=E2=80=99s table, and thus yesterday agreed to hand over a $25=
 million settlement.

=C2=A0

Alas, in business, realpolitik very often beats idealpolitik. Still, it=E2=
=80=99s possible to countenance the corporate pragmatism while also acknowl=
edging that this is all really bad for the Fourth Estate. (For the good fol=
ks at CBS News, it=E2=80=99s going to be hard to imagine that the Ellisons =
will
have their back more than Shari has, no matter how much Shell assures them.=
) On Friday, the Center for Journalism and Liberty characterized the expect=
ed Paramount settlement as =E2=80=9Ca payoff to the president whose F.C.C. =
has threatened to retaliate against coverage it doesn=E2=80=99t like by pul=
ling broadcast licenses and blocking mergers.=E2=80=9D Tough to argue with =
that.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

And it=E2=80=99s already inspiring others to wield litigation against
media organizations. Trump=E2=80=99s former co-campaign manager Chris LaCiv=
ita is preparing a defamation lawsuit against The Daily Beast, demanding a =
full retraction and apology over an article that suggested he was paid $22 =
million by the Trump campaign when, in fact, F.E.C. filings show his adviso=
ry firm received $19.2 million from the Trump campaign, the R.N.C., and rel=
ated super PACs. Historically, such errors would have warranted nothing mor=
e than a modest correction in italics.

Rumblings at Black Rock
-----------------------

Unsurprisingly, Shari=E2=80=99s impending settlement has left CBS News jour=
nalists,
and particularly 60 Minutes staff, in an uproar. Scott Pelley and Lesley St=
ahl, two of the most veteran 60 Minutes correspondents, are irate over the =
decision, according to their colleagues. Network sources say they would not=
 be surprised to see some staffers resign or speak out publicly if and when=
 the settlement is made. We=E2=80=99ll see.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Meanwhile, some
are questioning why CBS News C.E.O. Wendy McMahon and 60 Minutes executive =
producer Bill Owens are not standing up more forcefully for the news divisi=
on. Many of those folks were already upset with McMahon and Owens for chang=
es at Evening News (Owens is now E.P. on that show, too) that seem to leave=
 little room for the day=E2=80=99s political news: =E2=80=9CBad enough we h=
ave a revamped national evening newscast barely covering the incredibly swe=
eping
and consequential first full week of President Trump,=E2=80=9D one correspo=
ndent texted me. =E2=80=9CNow we get word we have an owner also eager to se=
ttle with him?=E2=80=9D

=C2=A0

Of course, the org chart dynamics here are already delicate. Shari has been=
 critical of McMahon for some time, and particularly over the network=E2=80=
=99s coverage of the Israel-Gaza conflict. She publicly (and memorably) cri=
ticized McMahon over her decision to
reprimand Tony Dokoupil for his hard-hitting interview with Ta-Nehisi Coate=
s, and then took Dokoupil to dinner in an overt sign of support. Earlier th=
is month, after the Anti-Defamation League and the American Jewish Committe=
e criticized 60 Minutes over its Israel-Gaza coverage, Shari directed CBS N=
ews to install former network president Susan Zirinsky as interim executive=
 editor.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

At times, it=E2=80=99s seemed as if McMahon were on the verge of losing her=
 job=E2=80=94which, to say the least, is not the strongest footing from whi=
ch to mount a protest against your boss. And even if she were to do so, she=
=E2=80=99d have to go through George Cheeks, the interim Paramount Global c=
o-C.E.O. who acts as an intermediary between Shari and Wendy, and who also =
has enough on his plate trying to navigate the Skydance deal to its conclus=
ion.

=C2=A0

In any event, the whole affair highlights the indignity of this particular =
moment in American journalism. It=E2=80=99s not enough that once-storied ne=
ws organizations must suffer through the contractions of their newsrooms, t=
he inexorable decline of their influence, the diminishment of talent salari=
es, and so forth. To add insult to injury, they must also endure corporate =
leaders who appear too beholden to their exit
packages and shareholders to stand up for their newsrooms, and newsroom lea=
ders who don=E2=80=99t have the leverage or intestinal fortitude to stand u=
p to them.

Perhaps worst of all, there=E2=80=99s no guarantee that Shari=E2=80=99s cap=
itulation to Trump will buy any less scrutiny of the Paramount sale. A mont=
h after Disney settled the Stephanopoulos defamation suit, Carr forced the =
F.C.C. to reopen complaints over how ABC News moderated the Harris-Trump de=
bate, which the
newly Republican-controlled agency said had been dismissed =E2=80=9Cprematu=
rely.=E2=80=9D For the new administration, the point of these legal tactics=
 isn=E2=80=99t simply to bully legacy media into servility, but to humiliat=
e them, too.

