28.799999999999997px;"><strong>Rumblings at Black Rock</strong></h3>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
<table width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" role=
=3D"presentation" style=3D"mso-table-lspace:0pt;mso-table-rspace:0pt;word-b=
reak:break-word;"><tbody><tr><td class=3D"r" style=3D"padding-bottom:32px;"=
><div style=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;Inter&#39;,&#39=
;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;line-height:1=
50%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"margin:0;margi=
n-bottom:0px;">Unsurprisingly, Shari=E2=80=99s impending settlement has lef=
t CBS News journalists,
and particularly <em>60 Minutes</em> staff, in an uproar. <strong>Scott Pel=
ley</strong> and <strong>Lesley Stahl</strong>, two of the most veteran <em=
>60 Minutes </em>correspondents, are irate over the decision, according to =
their colleagues. Network sources say they would not be surprised to see so=
me staffers resign or speak out publicly if and when the settlement is made=
=2E We=E2=80=99ll see.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"=
margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=
=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Meanwhile, some
are questioning why CBS News C.E.O. <strong>Wendy McMahon </strong>and <em>=
60 Minutes </em>executive producer <strong>Bill Owens </strong>are not stan=
ding up more forcefully for the news division. Many of those folks were <em=
>already </em>upset with McMahon and Owens for changes at <em>Evening News =
</em>(Owens is now E.P. on that show, too) that seem to leave little room f=
or the day=E2=80=99s political news: =E2=80=9CBad enough we have a revamped=
 national evening newscast barely covering the incredibly sweeping
and consequential first full week of President Trump,=E2=80=9D one correspo=
ndent texted me. =E2=80=9CNow we get word we have an owner also eager to se=
ttle with him?=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0<=
/p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Of course, the org chart dynami=
cs here are already delicate. Shari has been critical of McMahon for some t=
ime, and particularly over the network=E2=80=99s coverage of the Israel-Gaz=
a conflict. She publicly (and memorably) criticized McMahon over her decisi=
on to
reprimand <strong>Tony Dokoupil</strong> for his hard-hitting interview wit=
h <strong>Ta-Nehisi Coates</strong>, and then took Dokoupil to dinner in an=
 overt sign of support. Earlier this month, after the Anti-Defamation Leagu=
e and the American Jewish Committee criticized <em>60 Minutes</em> over its=
 Israel-Gaza coverage, Shari directed CBS News to install former network pr=
esident <strong>Susan Zirinsky </strong>as interim executive editor.=C2=A0<=
/p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">At times, it=E2=80=99s seemed as i=
f McMahon were on the verge of losing her job=E2=80=94which, to say the lea=
st, is not the strongest footing from which to mount a protest against your=
 boss. And even if she were to do so, she=E2=80=99d have to go through <str=
ong>George Cheeks</strong>, the interim Paramount Global co-C.E.O. who acts=
 as an intermediary between Shari and Wendy, and who <em>also </em>has enou=
gh on his plate trying to navigate the Skydance deal to its conclusion.</p>
<p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;mar=
gin-bottom:0px;">In any event, the whole affair highlights the indignity of=
 this particular moment in American journalism. It=E2=80=99s not enough tha=
t once-storied news organizations must suffer through the contractions of t=
heir newsrooms, the inexorable decline of their influence, the diminishment=
